# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tayside-children-s-hospital
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/1906-dundee-fire] In July 1906, the city of Dundee was the site of a large fire caused by the ignition of a bonded warehouse.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/1906-dundee-fire] The fire, which burned for 12 hours, has been described as the most destructive fire in the history of Dundee.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/1906-dundee-fire] The fire was described by an eyewitness as sending "rivers of burning whisky" through the city.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/1906-dundee-fire] James Watson and Co. were wholesale whisky merchants whose premises occupied a large site in Dundee on the corner of Trades Lane and Seagate.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/1906-dundee-fire] In 1906 about 300 people were employed by the firm.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/1906-dundee-fire] Watson and Co. were based at 97 Seagate with Customs Bond No.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/1906-dundee-fire] An employee of James Watson & Co. was passing the building on the evening of 19 July 1906 when he noticed smoke emerging from its roof.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/1906-dundee-fire] The building was soon ablaze and large vats of whisky caught fire and exploded, leading to flaming alcohol raining down on surrounding streets and buildings.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/1906-dundee-fire] The fire quickly spread to other buildings.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/1906-dundee-fire] The premises of another whisky merchant in nearby Candle Lane were also destroyed.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/1906-dundee-fire] So bad was the inferno that firefighters had to be called from Edinburgh to help fight it.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/1906-dundee-fire] The fire attracted thousands of spectators who gathered to watch the blaze and the sight of 'rivers of blue-flamed whiskey flowing into street drains'.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/1906-dundee-fire] At the time of the fire it was estimated that £450,000 worth of damage had been caused.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/1906-dundee-fire] The following year's Dundee Directory reported that the fire had 'desolated a large portion of the neighbourhood' around Seagate, Trades Lane and Candle Lane, and that as a result a large area for building operations had opened up.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/1906-dundee-fire] New bonds designed by David Baxter were built on the site in 1907 and are now listed buildings.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/1906-dundee-fire] Whisky blending at Watson's Bond ceased in 1981 and the bonds closed in 1987.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] The **2022 Kirkton riot** took place in the area of Kirkton in Dundee, Scotland on 31 October 2022.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] The civil unrest occurred on several streets in the area during Halloween and was caused by a large group of youths.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] The riot broke out at 17:30 GMT in Beauly Square following anti-social behaviour.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] Speculation arose that the riot broke out following a remembrance event for Grant Hutchison, a man who lived in Kirkton who had died in 2020.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] It was reported that vehicles and bins were torched on Beauly Square as the riot began to roll out.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] Other items such as bikes were also torched as rioters stole items from houses in the area.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] Police and emergency services began to arrive on the scene shortly afterwards, but were largely outnumbered by the rioters.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] Videos shared on social media showed rioters jumping and smashing car windows, youths setting numerous fires to Balgowan Avenue, the main road circulating through the area, blocking both ways as it was set alight.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] The nearby Old Glamis Road was also a target for rioters as bricks were thrown at cars and other vehicles.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] Vehicles such as cars were also targeted with bricks being thrown at windows and motorcycles and bins were set alight with debris remaining until the following day.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] A police helicopter was later dispatched at 20:00 GMT and fire engines arrived to the scene following the initial outbreak of the riot where they remained in the following hours.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] Academy was vandalised with windows being smashed open and cars being vandalised in the car park.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] Fireworks and firebombs were thrown to riot officers and emergency service officers who had arrived on the scene two hours prior, with one police officer receiving injuries.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] At 21:47 GMT, riot police tried to move rioters away from Gillburn Road.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] Shops and restaurants in Kirkton were targeted by rioters and as a result, windows were boarded up and closed the following day.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] The helicopter left the scene at 22:30 GMT after police managed to take control of the situation.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] No arrests were made during or the immediate aftermath of the riot however police stated that they would bring those responsible to justice.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] Police Scotland said that further police presence would be put in place for the days following the riot, up to and past Bonfire Night.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] Melted debris were later seen on roads throughout Kirkton the following morning.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] A press release was published the following morning from Police Scotland updating the public, stating that enquires were ongoing to identify rioters.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] On 1 November 2022, Scottish Labour MSP Michael Marra and Scottish Conservative MSP Maurice Golden submitted an urgent question to the Scottish Parliament following the riots, seeking clarity from the Scottish Government and question how such an event could be stopped in future.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] As a result of the riot, several venues in Dundee cancelled their Bonfire Night displays.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] Dundee's annual fireworks display for Bonfire Night did not go ahead for the third year, with a local councillor stating "There is already enough rockets in the community to offset the ban of fireworks".
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] Following the riot, Dundee City Council leader John Alexander called for supermarkets in Dundee to ban the public selling of fireworks.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] Supermarkets shortly after in Dundee banned the public selling of fireworks.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] On 1 November 2022, Scottish Government Justice Secretary Keith Brown confirmed that Police Scotland had launched an investigation to identify and prosecute those involved in the riot.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] Brown also faced calls to introduce a nationwide ban on public purchase of fireworks following the events after he condemned the riot.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] On 3 November 2022, a teenager was arrested in connection with the riot.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] On 6 November 2022, a 28-year old woman and a 15-year old teenager were charged following the riot.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] On 27 October 2023, Police Scotland revealed that 33 people were charged following the riot.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] In November 2025, four men stood trial at Falkirk Sheriff Court in connection with the disorder that took place.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] After an eight-day trial involving more than 160 hours of CCTV evidence and testimony from 18 Crown witnesses, a jury convicted two men of breaching the peace.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] One man was found to have incited others during the disorder, while the other was found to have acted with others to throw fireworks and projectiles at police and members of the public, start fires in the area, damage property, and encourage others to join the unrest.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] Two additional men on trial were acquitted by verdicts of not proven.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] Before the trial began, three men had already pled guilty to separate charges of breaching the peace in connection with the incident.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] Sentencing for all those convicted was deferred pending background reports.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] Earlier in the proceedings, two men faced no further action after the court upheld no-case-to-answer submissions from their solicitors.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] In both 2023 and 2024, further incidents took place in the same area.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] In 2023, a disturbance took place once again on Beauly Avenue on 31 October, albeit a smaller scale, when a fire broke out.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] Riot police were deployed alongside fifteen police vehicles.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] Over 50 people were involved in the disturbance.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] In the lead up to Halloween in 2024, eleven vacant houses were secured by police in Kirkton in preparation of any rioting breaking out.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] On the night of Halloween, bins were set alight in the area.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] Dundee City Council leader John Alexander condemned the scenes from Kirkton.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] Alexander said that he'd never seen anything in the decades he lived in the area and compared the riot to scenes of a 'war-torn nation'.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] Many media outlets and users on social media compared the riots to the 2013 horror film, *The Purge*.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] A poster was created parodying the film which featured "The Purge: Kirkton".
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] Dundee City West MSP Joe FitzPatrick and Dundee City East MSP Shona Robison wrote a joint letter to the police commissioner following the incident.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] Police Scotland condemned the incident and publicly stated that police presence would be tighter as a result of the riots.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] Several residents criticised Police Scotland's approach as they accused them of not responding to the situation sooner as no arrests were made during or in the immediate aftermath of the riot.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] The Scottish Government's Justice Secretary Keith Brown described the riot as appalling and wholly unacceptable.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/2022-kirkton-riot] The Kirkton riot was the subject of a 2023 documentary series produced by the BBC, *Street Gangs*.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] The **Abertay Historical Society** (**AHS**) is a historical society based in Dundee, Scotland.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] It aims to promote interest in history, with a special focus on the history of Perthshire, Angus and Fife.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] The AHS runs a regular programme of public lectures on historical topics and also organises special events.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] The Society also publishes books, usually producing at least one publication per year.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] The Society was founded at a meeting held at University College, Dundee on 29 May 1947.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] The founders were the Principal of University College, Major-General Douglas Wimberley, and the college's history lecturer, Dr Frederick T Wainwright.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] It has been suggested that the Society was promoted as part of a process of developing 'town and gown links' in Dundee by Wimberley.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] The AHS was set up with the goal of encouraging the study of local history in the Abertay area (Perthshire, Angus and northern Fife).
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] The Society pursued this aim by organising regular talks and lectures as well as other events such as excursions.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] The Society formerly had an Archaeological Section which organised excavations in the local area and its own series of meetings.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] However, in 1993 the activities of this section came under the control of the Society's Council.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] For a time in the 1970s the AHS also had an Industrial Archaeology Section, which mainly sought to record the region's industrial heritage.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] In 2015 the archaeological activities of the Society were taken over by a newly established fieldwork division, which has undertaken projects including the recording of stones that survive from the demolished Dundee Royal Arch.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] Since 1953 the Society has published books on local history, the first of which was *Dundee and the American Civil War* by David Carrie.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] A number of notable historians and authors have written volumes published by the Society including Bruce Lenman, Andrew Murray Scott and Christopher Whatley.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] The 51st AHS publication *Ten Taysiders: Forgotten Figures from Dundee, Angus and Perthshire* was published in 2011 and was edited by members of the Society's Council.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] In 2011 the AHS began to make copies of out-of-print titles available for free download from their website.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] The Society's publications are regularly cited in academic literature.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] As well as running events, the AHS has undertaken various heritage activities.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] The Society has lobbied for the preservation of local buildings and historic sites, and played a key role in the creation of Dundee Civic Trust and Dundee Heritage Trust.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] The Abertay Historical Society was also a benefactor of The McManus: Dundee's Art Gallery and Museum Fundraising Appeal which allowed the restoration and refurbishment of Dundee's main museum and galleries between 2006 and 2009.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] A number of notable individuals have been associated with the Abertay Historical Society.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] These include Sir Francis Mudie who was President of the Society from 1963 to 1965 and also contributed to its publications.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] Another key figure in the society's history was S.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] Edgar Lythe, a founder member who went on to be Vice Principal of the University of Strathclyde.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] Lythe, who edited and wrote several of the Society's publications, was credited with moving the AHS away from simply organising events and towards actively encouraging research into local history.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] The Dundee bibliophile and antiquarian Catherine Kinnear was a founder member of the Society and later went on to be its president.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] The AHS has been described as "one of Scotland's most successful local history organisations".
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] It organises a regular programme of evening lectures, which are usually held in Discovery Point, Dundee, although other venues are also used from time to time.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] These lectures cover a wide range of topics relating to the local area.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] The Society also works with other Dundee-based groups to run the Dundee Afternoon Lectures series.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] Some events are held jointly with other local groups.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] For example, in 2010 the AHS joined with the Perth Strathspey and Reel Society to have an event at the A.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] Bell Library, Perth entitled "The Fiddle Music of Perth" as part of the Perth 800 celebrations.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] In 2011 the AHS contributed to the Dundee Science Festival by organising a public lecture on the design and construction of the Bell Rock Lighthouse.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] The Society is a partner in Great War Dundee, a project commemorating the First World War, and its impact on Dundee set up to mark the centenary of the conflict.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] The Society is run by a council whose membership includes the President, General Secretary, other office bearers and various ordinary members.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] In addition the Lord Provost of Dundee, the Provost of Perth and Kinross, the Provost of Angus, the Principal of the University of Dundee and the Principal of the University of St Andrews all serve as Honorary Presidents of the Society.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] As noted above the Abertay Historical Society was founded at what was then University College, Dundee by my members of that institution's staff.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] Since that time the AHS has maintained close links with the institution, which has since 1967 been known as the University of Dundee.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] The Principal of the University of Dundee is one five Honorary Presidents of the Society, and many of the Society's members and office-holders, including past presidents, have been University staff and students.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] Equally many of its publications have been authored by figures connected with the university and the AHS' lecture programme has offers University staff and students the chance to present their research to the local community.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] An annual prize is awarded by the AHS to the undergraduate at the University of Dundee who produces the dissertation which makes the most significant contribution to local history.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] Some of these dissertations have been expanded and published by the AHS.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] 44 *Scottish Cowboys and the Dundee Investors* by Claire E.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] Swan evolved from a dissertation which won the Abertay History Prize in 2003.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] Julie Danskin, author of the Society's 54th publication is also a past winner of the Abertay History Prize.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] The archives of the AHS are held by Archive Services at the University of Dundee.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] Currently most of the Society's lectures are held at the university, usually in the Dalhousie Building.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] The first publication by the society was *Dundee and the American Civil War* which was published in 1953 and was written by one of the Society's members, David Carrie.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] An editorial note in the publication announced that it was hoped, if finances allowed, that it would to 'be followed by others of similar character, produced to a uniform size to simplify binding into convenient volumes'.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] It was also stated that while its publications would 'always have a strong local flavour the Society aims to avoid undue parochialism and seeks to set its studies against the wide backcloth of general historical development'.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] As of December 2015 the Society has published a further 55 books relating to the history of Tayside and Fife.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] Members of the Society are sent a free copy of each new publication, while other copies are made available for sale either from the Society or via booksellers.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] The publications have covered a wide number of topics and have varied in style.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] While most are monographs some titles have been collections of essays written by various authors.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] An example of the latter is the 2011 publication *Ten Taysiders* which featured biographical essays on ten historic figures from Dundee, Perthshire and Angus, such as Mary Ann Baxter, A.K.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] Bell and William Sharpey and which was written by various authors including Steve Connelly, Fiona Scharlau, Charles Waterston, Graham Lowe, John MacEwen, John Kerr, William Kenefick and Kenneth Baxter.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-historical-society] The Society has undertaken a programme of making digital versions of some of its out of print publications available for free download from its website.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] Abertay launched the world's first computer games degree in 1997 and in 2017 held a programme of events celebrating 20 Years of Games.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] Abertay was also the first to offer a degree in Ethical Hacking, starting in 2006.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] In 1872 Sir David Baxter, 1st Baronet of Kilmaron, died and bequeathed £20,000 (£1.96 million adjusting for inflation) for the establishment of a mechanics' institute in Dundee.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] The Baxter bequest was intended to create an educational establishment permitting young male working mechanics and other craftsmen to better themselves.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] After some years of delay the trustees finalised a scheme and met the conditions of the bequest and the Dundee Technical Institute opened on 15 October 1888 in grounds, purchased from University College, Dundee, adjacent to Small's Wynd, Dundee.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] In 1901 the Dundee Technical Institute enrolled 723 part-time students and was one of the first education hubs to be recognised as a 'central institution' by the Scotch Education Department.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] In 1906 a new site in Bell Street, Dundee was purchased to build a larger complex to accommodate a growing student population.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] In 1911 the completed complex was formally opened as the Dundee Technical College & School of Art.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] In 1909 James Duncan of Jordanstone left £60,000 (£6.17 million adjusting for inflation) to establish an art college in Dundee.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] The college of art became a formally separate institution, known as the Duncan of Jordanstone College of Art and Design, in 1975, remaining independent until 1994 when it became part of the University of Dundee.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] The First World War reduced enrolments and growth but the vocational nature of the institute meant that its classes were relevant to the war effort.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] The first women students enrolled in 1914.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] After the Second World War enrolments and the scope of delivery continued to expand, as did the reputation of the institute.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] By 1951 the institute was teaching courses that led to examinations for the external degrees of the University of London in pharmacy, mechanical, civil, and electrical engineering.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] In 1955 the National Council for Technological Awards was established and validated diplomas in technology which were equivalent in standard if not in name to honours degrees.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] The institution began offering degrees itself in 1956.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] Abertay University was created in 1994, under the Further and Higher Education Act 1992, granting the title "University of Abertay Dundee" to the Dundee Institute of Technology.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] Since 2014 the university has promoted itself as Abertay University.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] The university's name was formally changed to Abertay University by an Order of Council on 1 September 2019.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] Abertay was the first university in the world to offer a "computer games" degree in 1997.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] Abertay was the UK's first university to be recognised as a Centre for Excellence in Computer Games Education, and is associated with a business support programme for computer game startups.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] Abertay University is situated in the centre of Dundee.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] The campus buildings include the historic Old College buildings of Dundee Business School, the Bernard King Library, and others.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] The Bernard King Library in Bell Street opened to learners in February 1998 and was formally opened by Queen Elizabeth II on 30 June 1998.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] The library was voted best new building in Scotland in the 1998 Scottish Design Awards competition.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] The Abertay cyberQuarter opened in June 2022 with they key aim of bringing together students, academics, and organisations to help solve global cybersecurity challenges.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] The centre offers a physical space for collaboration and experimentation using digital tools and technologies.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] Abertay is a small university that receives the majority of its funding for teaching rather than research.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] Nevertheless, according to the results of the Research Excellence Framework 2014 (REF2014), Abertay was the highest ranked modern university in Scotland for 'research intensity'.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] The university submitted an increased proportion of staff in REF2014 compared to RAE2008 and achieved an average score of 2.15 – which in REF terms means "quality that is recognised internationally in terms of originality, significance, and rigour".
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] This was an improvement from the average score of 1.83, "national recognition", achieved in RAE2008.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] The Research Excellence Framework 2021 (REF2021) published on 12 May 2022 and Abertay recorded a 23% increase in research that is "internationally excellent" or "world-leading" since the last REF in 2014.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] In 2009 it established the UK's first Centre for Excellence in Computer Games Education, and a business support programme.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] Abertay runs five of the 25 interactive and games degree courses accredited in the UK by Creative Skillset, the industry skills body for the creative sector, more than any other institution.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] The university was established by a statutory instrument The University of Abertay Dundee (Scotland) Order of Council 1994.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] The order sets out the objects of the university and the general functions of the University Court to 'conduct the affairs of the university and carry out and promote its objects'.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] Abertay was the UK's first University to be recognised as a Centre for Excellence in Computer Games Education.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] The Centre for Excellence is accredited by Skillset and has strong links with industrial partners from across the broadcast, interactive and wider digital media sectors.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] These partners include BBC Scotland, BBC Vision, BSkyB, Channel 4, Electronic Arts, Codemasters, Blitz Games Studios, Rare, Sony Computer Entertainment Europe, Microsoft and Disney Interactive.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] Abertay was the first university in the world to have a degree in Ethical Hacking, differentiating from its other cyber-security degree counterparts by taking a more offensive approach to security.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] The university began to offer this degree in 2006.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] In 2020 the university was one of eight in the UK, and the only one in Scotland, to be named an Academic Centre of Excellence in Cybersecurity by the National Cybersecurity Centre.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] The university is also home to the Ethical Hacking society, which hosts the Securi-Tay conference, the largest student-run security conference in Europe.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] Abertay provides a range of short courses that provide the public with opportunities to improve current skills and enhance knowledge in several areas including digital marketing and sustainability.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] Fully funded by the Scottish Funding Council, the courses are free to applicants.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] Each short course is credit-bearing and a recognised university qualification.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] Prior to 1953 no coat of arms was registered in the name of the college.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] The original Ensigns Armorial were recorded in the Public Register of All Arms and Bearings in Scotland on 25 July 1953, in the name of Dundee Technical College.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] They were subsequently transferred to Dundee College of Technology in 1977, then to Dundee Institute of Technology in 1988 and, finally, to the University of Abertay Dundee on 25 April 1994.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] The top left sector is taken from the arms of Sir David Baxter of Kilmaron, who bequeathed a significant sum of money in order to establish the original Dundee Technical Institute in 1888.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] The top right sector is taken from the arms of Sir William Dalgleish, who was the senior trustee of what by then was known as Dundee Technical College and School of Art, and who opened the first building – Old College – on Abertay's present campus on Bell Street in 1911.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] The top middle sector of three chevrons is the heraldic symbol for "technical".
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] The pot of lilies in base is taken from the arms of the City of Dundee, with the books on either side representing education.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] Aaron McCauley, a graduate of Abertay, designed and registered the Abertay tartan in 2003.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] The tartan is based on Abertay's promotional colours of dark blue, red, gold and green from its coat of arms.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] The Abertay Students' Association (Abertay SA) is based in the ground floor of the Bernard King library building.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] Abertay SA co-ordinates all societies and acts as the voice and representation of all of Abertay's students.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] Abertay University has a wide group of sports teams competing under the university banner.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] It ranges from Tennis to Hockey who compete in the BUCS (British Universities & Colleges Sport) leagues, which competes against other universities and colleges in Scotland.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] The Football, Hockey and Basketball teams have their 1st teams competing in the highest league (BUCS 1A).
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/abertay-university] The university has a fierce rivalry with Dundee University, competing in a yearly Varsity competition.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/al-maktoum-college-of-higher-education] The college offers postgraduate programmes in the study of Islam, Economics, and Arabic.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/al-maktoum-college-of-higher-education] The college offered degree programs but agreements with Universities have been withdrawn, including Aberdeen.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/al-maktoum-college-of-higher-education] The College's partnership agreement with the university of Aberdeen was terminated in September 2012.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/al-maktoum-college-of-higher-education] All students previously enrolled on higher education programmes at the College were transferred to the university of Aberdeen.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/al-maktoum-college-of-higher-education] The college has been reviewed by the Quality Assurance Agency for Higher Education a number of times, and since 2018 it meets UK standards.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/al-maktoum-college-of-higher-education] According to the report, in January 2018 the college had 18 registered students, 6 academic staff, 5 visiting fellows, and 6 administrative staff.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/al-maktoum-college-of-higher-education] Malory Nye was principal of the college until June 2011 when he was dismissed from his post, together with his wife, Isabel Campbell-Nye, who was head of the English language centre.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/al-maktoum-college-of-higher-education] The couple alleged that the director of operations, and chairman of the college's board of directors decided to force them out because they're white, British Christians, among other claims.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/al-maktoum-college-of-higher-education] However, all claims were dismissed at an employment tribunal in Glasgow.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/al-maktoum-college-of-higher-education] The couple also lodged grievances against the chancellor of the college, the Lord, Baron Elder for his handling of the process.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/al-maktoum-college-of-higher-education] Following the investigation, he issued an apology for his minor breaches of the Code of Conduct.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The site was previously occupied by a mansion known as Alder Hey which the local poor law guardians acquired for use as a children's home in 1910.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The mansion was converted for use as a military hospital in 1914.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the First World War, the United States Army established Camp Hospital 40 on the site, operated by Hospital Unit Q and, subsequently, Unit W.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] American sources commonly refer to Alder Hey as being within Liverpool's Knotty Ash area.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the Second World War, parts of the hospital were again used to treat injured military personnel.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The Liverpool Neonatal Surgical Unit opened at the hospital in 1953.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] This unit was the first neonatal intensive care unit in the United Kingdom.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The opening was largely due to the efforts of Isabella Forshall, a paediatric surgeon.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1990 when Myrtle Street Children's Hospital (founded in 1869 and previously known as Royal Liverpool Children's Hospital) closed, Alder Hey absorbed its A&E department.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital authority was one of 57 such bodies which became an NHS hospital trust in 1991.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Ronald McDonald House, a home for the families of sick children, opened in 1993.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1999 an inquiry was instituted into the Alder Hey organs scandal and to investigate the hospital's practices in respect of removal and retention of human tissue.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The inquiry had far-reaching effects throughout the UK hospital system and provided the impetus for the Human Tissue Act 2004.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In August 2008 the Royal Liverpool Children's NHS Trust became an NHS foundation trust and changed its name to Alder Hey NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Between 2010 and 2014 the number of doctors employed at the trust increased from 269 to 344, while the number of managers increased from 70 to 86.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] At the end of March 2017, the trust was confirmed as one of four additional NHS Global Digital Exemplars, joining the twelve announced in September 2016.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey had its centenary year in 2014, the last year in which it operated from the buildings on its original site.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A new hospital was procured under Private Finance Initiative contract in neighbouring Springfield Park.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The works, which were carried out by Laing O'Rourke at a cost of £187 million, began on 26 March 2013 and the hospital opened in October 2015.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It was Europe's first children's hospital built in a park.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The original Alder Hey buildings were mostly demolished and the land was reclaimed as new parkland for the surrounding community.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Features of the new hospital include access to play areas, natural light and striking views of the park are available wherever possible Children and young people were involved with the design of the new hospital.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A drawing of a flower by teenage patient Eleanor Brogan impressed architects and inspired their final design.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital is a centre of excellence for oncology and muscular dystrophy as well as spinal, heart and brain conditions.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey has Europe's first 3T Intraoperative MRI scanner which is a pioneering technology for neurosurgery, providing surgeons with extremely high resolution images and reducing the need for repeat operations in 90% of cases.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It currently employs about 2,400 staff and treats over 270,000 children from across the UK each year.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey conducts paediatric research into children's medicines, infection, inflammation and oncology.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It has research partners including the University of Liverpool and is a member of Liverpool Health Partners.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey conducts more than 100 clinical research studies on an ongoing basis, ranging from observation to clinical trials.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital is within the National Institute for Health and Care Research's Top 100 Performing Trust's for participation recruitment in 2013/14.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey was a finalist in the Clinical Research Impact category of the 2013 HSJ Awards and in 2014 the innovation team received the Health Service Journal Award for improving health care with technology.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2016 the first phase of a bespoke research, education and innovation centre, Institute in the Park, opened next to Alder Hey in the Park.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In November 2015, the institute hosted a children's health Hackathon in conjunction with Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey Children's Charity supports the work of the hospital.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In addition to NHS funding which covers the running costs of the hospital, Alder Hey relies on charitable support.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Funds are spent directly on initiatives in the hospital to benefit patients.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It funds research initiatives, patient and family enhancements and state of the art medical equipment.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Known as the 'Imagine Appeal' until 2012, Alder Hey Children's Charity is based within the hospital.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] On 14 October 2013 the charity launched a public appeal to raise £30m to fund equipment, facilities and research at Alder Hey's new hospital, Alder Hey in the Park.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In October 2015 the charity announced over £20m had been raised.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2009 charitable support allowed Alder Hey to buy Europe's first 3T intraoperative MRI scanner.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In one charitably funded project, the sound recordist and musician Chris Watson was employed to devise an art project, using bird song recordings made by children to calm other young patients as they received injections and other treatments.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1978, the charity Art For Their Sake, a team of volunteer artists led by founder George Nicholas (now of Ormskirk, England), produced the world's longest mural in the corridors of Alder Hey Children's Hospital.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A Guinness Record was set with a total of 17,963 square feet of murals, and awarded to the hospital in 1986.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Nicholas and his team continued to work on these murals for a period of 30 years, adding to as well as restoring and maintaining, for a total of over 34,000 square feet.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey runs an Arts for Health programme, funded entirely through charitable sources including Alder Hey Children's Charity.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme aims to enhance the experience of being a patient and includes animation projects, music and dance therapy, creative writing, comedy workshops and storytelling.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] An international child health development programme led by Alder Hey clinicians focuses on humanitarian work in developing countries.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme includes provision of immediate medical support, knowledge sharing and involvement with international clinical trials.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme has undertaken work across Africa and Asia, including Pakistan, Malawi, Nepal and India.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the 1990s, Alder Hey was featured in the BBC television series *Children's Hospital*.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2011, chef Heston Blumenthal took to the challenge of changing the dinner menu of Alder Hey Children's Hospital on his televised show, *Heston's Mission Impossible*.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Since September 2012, Alder Hey has regularly featured on the CBBC television series *Operation Ouch!*.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In October 2013, the Care Quality Commission's Intelligent Monitoring system placed Alder Hey in category one, meaning it would be amongst the first hospitals to be inspected under a new style of inspection.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In May 2014, Alder Hey was inspected by the Care Quality Commission and was given the overall rating Requires Improvement.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In June 2015, Alder Hey was re-inspected by the Care Quality Commission and was given the overall rating Good, and was rated Outstanding in the Caring category.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Another inspection took place in 2018, the overall rating was unchanged.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Dame Josephine Williams was appointed Chair of the Trust Board in February 2019.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Louise Shepherd CBE was appointed Chief Executive of the trust in March 2008.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] On 26 January 2023, the Alder Hey Children's Hospital NHS Foundation Trust was granted the Honorary Freedom of the Metropolitan Borough of Sefton.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Angus was historically a province, and later a sheriffdom and county (called **Forfarshire** or the **County of Forfar** until 1928), bordering Kincardineshire to the north-east, Aberdeenshire to the north and Perthshire to the west; southwards it faced Fife across the Firth of Tay.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] The county included Dundee until 1894, when it was made a county of a city.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] The pre-1894 boundaries of Angus continue to be used as a registration county.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Between 1975 and 1996 Angus was a lower-tier district within the Tayside region.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] The district took on its modern form and powers in 1996, since when the local authority has been Angus Council.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] The name "Angus" indicates the territory of the eighth-century Pictish king, Óengus I.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] The area that now comprises Angus has been occupied since at least the Neolithic period.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Material taken from postholes from an enclosure at Douglasmuir, near Friockheim, about 5 mi (8 km) north of Arbroath has been radiocarbon dated to around 3500 BC.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] The function of the enclosure is unknown, but may have been for agriculture or for ceremonial purposes.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Bronze Age archaeology is to be found in abundance in the area.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Examples include the short-cist burials found near West Newbigging, about a mile to the North of the town.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] These burials included pottery urns, a pair of silver discs and a gold armlet.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Iron Age archaeology is also well represented, for example in the souterrain nearby Warddykes cemetery and at West Grange of Conan, as well as the better-known examples at Carlungie and Ardestie.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] The county is traditionally associated with the Pictish territory of Circin, which is thought to have encompassed Angus and the Mearns.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Bordering it were the kingdoms of Cé (Mar and Buchan) to the North, Fotla (Atholl) to the West, and Fib (Fife) to the South.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] The most visible remnants of the Pictish age are the numerous sculptured stones that can be found throughout Angus.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Of particular note are the collections found at Aberlemno, St Vigeans, Kirriemuir and Monifieth.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Angus is first recorded as one of the provinces of Scotland in 937, when Dubacan, the Mormaer of Angus, is recorded in the *Chronicle of the Kings of Alba* as having died at the Battle of Brunanburh.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] The signing of the Declaration of Arbroath at Arbroath Abbey in 1320 marked Scotland's establishment as an independent nation.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Partly on this basis, Angus is marketed as the birthplace of Scotland.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] It is an area of rich history from Pictish times onwards.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Notable historic sites in addition to Arbroath Abbey include Glamis Castle, Arbroath Signal Tower museum and the Bell Rock Lighthouse, described as one of the Seven Wonders of the Industrial World.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] During the 16th and 17th century, several witch trials took place in Forfar, the last of which took place in 1662 and in which 52 people were accused.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] At the time, Forfar was a town of around 1,000 inhabitants, with an additional 2,000 people residing in the county.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Angus was one of the ancient provinces of Scotland, under the authority of the Mormaer or Earl of Angus.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] From at least the thirteenth century the area formed the basis for a shire (the area administered by a sheriff) based in Forfar: the Sheriff of Forfar.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Over time, Scotland's shires became more significant than the old provinces, with more administrative functions being given to the sheriffs.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] The older territory called Angus was therefore gradually eclipsed in legal importance by the shire of Forfar (or Forfarshire) which covered the same area.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] In 1667 Commissioners of Supply were established for each shire, which would serve as the main administrative body for the area until the creation of county councils in 1890.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Following the Acts of Union in 1707, the English term 'county' came to be used interchangeably with the older term 'shire'.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Elected county councils were established in 1890 under the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1889, taking most of the functions of the commissioners (which were eventually abolished in 1930).
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] The county's five largest burghs, being Arbroath, Brechin, Dundee, Forfar, and Montrose, were deemed capable of managing their own affairs and so were excluded from the administrative area of the county council.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] The county council held its first official meeting on 22 May 1890 at the County Buildings (now known as Forfar Sheriff Court), the county's main courthouse, which also served as the meeting place for the commissioners of supply.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Robert Haldane-Duncan, 3rd Earl of Camperdown, a Liberal peer, was appointed the first chairman of the county council.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] The 1889 Act also led to a review of boundaries, with exclaves being transferred to a county they actually bordered, and parishes which straddled more than one county being adjusted such that each parish was entirely in a single county.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] There were several such changes affecting the boundaries of Forfarshire.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Dundee was subsequently made a county of itself in 1894, also removing the city from Forfarshire for judicial and lieutenancy purposes.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Arbroath, Brechin, Forfar and Montrose were brought within the administrative area of the county council in 1930, although Arbroath was classed as a large burgh, allowing its council to continue to deliver most local government functions itself.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] In May 1928 the county council resolved to use the name 'Angus' for the area rather than the 'County of Forfar'.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] The council petitioned the government to officially change the name too.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] The government responded by directing all departments to use Angus, but noted that the legal name would remain Forfar until such time as it could be changed by statute.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] The statutory change of name from Forfar to Angus eventually took place in 1947 under the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1947.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Angus County Council was abolished in 1975 under the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973, which replaced Scotland's counties, burghs and landward districts with a two-tier structure of upper-tier regions and lower-tier districts.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] A new Angus district was created covering most of the pre-1975 county, with the exceptions being that Monifieth and a number of villages immediately north of Dundee were transferred to an enlarged City of Dundee district, and Kettins was transferred to Perth and Kinross.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Angus District Council was a lower-tier district level authority subordinate to the Tayside Regional Council.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] A lieutenancy area covering the same area as the new district was created at the same time.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Further local government reforms in 1996 under the Local Government etc.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] (Scotland) Act 1994 saw the regions and districts created in 1975 abolished and replaced with council areas providing all local government services.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Angus district became one of the new council areas, taking on the functions of the abolished Tayside Regional Council.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] The council area regained Monifieth and the villages north of Dundee as part of the same reforms.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] The Angus lieutenancy area was adjusted to match the new council area in 1996.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] The Lord Lieutenant of Angus is appointed by the monarch.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] The boundaries of the historic county of Angus (as it was prior to the removal of Dundee in 1894) are still used for some limited official purposes connected with land registration, being a registration county.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Angus can be split into three geographic areas.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] To the north and west, the topography is mountainous.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] This is the area of the Grampian Mountains, Mounth hills and Five Glens of Angus, which is sparsely populated and where the main industry is hill farming.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Glas Maol – the highest point in Angus at 1,068 metres (3,504 feet) – can be found here, on the tripoint boundary with Perthshire and Aberdeenshire.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] To the south and east the topography consists of rolling hills (such as the Sidlaws) bordering the sea; this area is well populated, with the larger towns.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] In between lies Strathmore (*the Great Valley*), which is a fertile agricultural area noted for the growing of potatoes, soft fruit and the raising of Aberdeen Angus cattle.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Montrose in the north east of the county is notable for its tidal basin and wildlife.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Angus's coast is fairly regular, the most prominent features being the headlands of Scurdie Ness and Buddon Ness.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] In the 2001 census, the population of Angus was recorded as 108,400.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Of the 16 to 74 age group, 32.84% had no formal qualifications, 27.08% were educated to 'O' Grade/Standard Grade level, 14.38% to Higher level, 7.64% to HND or equivalent level and 18.06% to degree level.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] The most recent available census results (2001) show that Gaelic is spoken by 0.45% of the Angus population.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] This, similar to other lowland areas, is lower than the national average of 1.16%.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] These figures are self-reported and are not broken down into levels of fluency.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Meanwhile, the 2011 census found that 38.4% of the population in Angus can speak Scots, above the Scottish average of 30.1%.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] This puts Angus as the council area with the sixth highest proficiency in Scots, behind only Shetland, Orkney, Moray, Aberdeenshire, and East Ayrshire.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 111,587 residents aged three and over, 43,917 (39.4%) considered themselves able to speak or read the Scots language.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] This puts Angus as the council area with the fifth highest proficiency in Scots, ahead of Orkney.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Historically, the dominant language in Angus was Pictish until the sixth to seventh centuries AD when the area became progressively gaelicised, with Pictish extinct by the mid-ninth century.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Gaelic/Middle Irish began to retreat from lowland areas in the late-eleventh century and was absent from the Eastern lowlands by the fourteenth century.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] It was replaced there by Middle Scots, the contemporary local South Northern dialect of Modern Scots, while Gaelic persisted as a majority language in the Highlands and Hebrides until the 19th century.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Angus Council are planning to raise the status of Gaelic in the county by adopting a series of measures, including bilingual road signage, communications, vehicle livery and staffing.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 111,590 residents aged three and over, 933 (0.8%) considered themselves able to speak or read Gaelic, this represents an increase from the 588 (0.5%) from the 2011 census.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] As of 2018 Angus is divided into 25 community council areas and all apart from Friockheim district have an active council.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Angus is represented by two MPs for the UK Parliament.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Angus is represented by two constituency MSPs for the Scottish Parliament.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] In addition to the two constituency MSPs, Angus is also represented by seven MSPs for the North East Scotland electoral region.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] The Edinburgh-Aberdeen railway line runs along the coast, through Dundee and the towns of Monifieth, Carnoustie, Arbroath and Montrose.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] There is a small airport at Dundee, which at present operates flights to London and Belfast.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/angus-scotland] Arbroath is the largest town in the modern county, followed by Forfar, the county town and administrative centre, and Montrose.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/tayside-children-s-hospital] The concept of establishing a children's hospital in Dundee had been under consideration since 1995.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/tayside-children-s-hospital] Approval for the construction of the facility was granted in 1999, and the development proceeded in two stages: the initial phase comprised a set of laboratories, while the second phase encompassed the creation of family-friendly accommodation for parents.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/tayside-children-s-hospital] The new facility was officially inaugurated by television personality Fred MacAulay on 7 June 2006.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/tayside-children-s-hospital] In the facility is a 40-bed children's medical ward which includes a six-bed High Dependency Unit and the Paediatric Assessment Unit.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/tayside-children-s-hospital] An outdoor play area and a large indoor play centre is run by staff.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/tayside-children-s-hospital] Close to the children's wards is the Ronald McDonald suites for parents to reside in while their child is in hospital.
[src:tayside-children-s-hospital/tayside-children-s-hospital] Tayside Children's Hospital also extends beyond the Ninewells site with the Children's Ambulatory Care Unit located at Perth Royal Infirmary.
